title: Use cudaMemsetAsync and add checks on CUDA calls.
body:
**Description**:
Use `cudaMemsetAsync` instead of `cudaMemset` for tensors known to be in device memory (for clarity).
Add error checks on a few CUDA calls that are missing it:  `CUDA_RETURN_IF_ERROR`

**Motivation and Context**
CUDA memset functions are already asynchronous when the memory is on device (see below).  ROCm memset functions behave slightly differently between `hipMemset` and `hipMemsetAsync`.  The ROCm execution provider code is generated from CUDA code.  In the future, the code for CUDA/ROCm will be better shared.  So to improve performance in ROCm and for clarity, use the async variants in as many places as possible.

https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-runtime-api/api-sync-behavior.html#api-sync-behavior__memcpy-sync
"The synchronous memset functions are asynchronous with respect to the host except when the target is pinned host memory or a Unified Memory region, in which case they are fully synchronous. The Async versions are always asynchronous with respect to the host."

labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
This PR was split from the PR [5480](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5480), which was to make the original PR easier for code review. 

This PR is mostly about GPU kernels for ROCm EP. Due to similar GPU programming language (CUDA and [HIP](https://rocmdocs.amd.com/en/latest/Programming_Guides/HIP-FAQ.html#how-does-porting-cuda-to-hip-compare-to-porting-cuda-to-opencl) and similar math library calls, one principle in ROCM EP design is to share CUDA kernels as much as possible for ROCm. Thus, the script amd_hipify.py has been created for converting CUDA kernels to ROCm HIP kernels automatically during compilation phase. But, for some reasons such as perf issue, syntax difference..., some converted kernels need some manual intervention. These kernels will be checked in the repo physically for now. In order to avoid manual intervention, the plan is to refactor CUDA kernels to make them portable between CUDA EP and ROCm EP as much as possible.

Please refer to "HIP Porting [Guide"](https://rocmdocs.amd.com/en/latest/Programming_Guides/HIP-porting-guide.html#hip-porting-guide) for details.

body:
Memory profiling tool to enable memory analysis and visualization

1. We can create as many sessions  (pids) as we need, each session can be customized to display a certain group of tensors. E.g,  in the following graph, we have 7 sessions. Pid0 displays all statically-planned activations. Pid1 displays all dynamically-planed activations.  Pid 5, 6, 8, 9 are customized to create a certain group of tensors that are with interest (In the example, they are all the gradients that run on a 4-rank distributed run).  Pid10 and 11 are some other customized groups.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/49965641/97818299-95261c00-1c56-11eb-8670-686264341139.png)

2. If we zoom into one session "GPU (static activation) (pid0)". (Other groups have similar layout):
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/49965641/97818388-006fee00-1c57-11eb-987b-05b1a6535b2e.png)

3. X-axis is the memory address (even though it is displayed at time, this is just the default unit of chrome::tracing).  All the memories are started with offset 0. 
	a. We have separated the memory types into 3 categories (in the data structure  MemoryInfo::MapType). (1) Initializer, (2) statically planed activation. (3), dynamically planned activation.

4. Y-axis is the execution step (the order or "program counter" decided by the execution planner.   Note, to reduce the trace size, we did not record every step, so the PC values are dis-continuous, we only record the steps that have changes (e.g,  some tensors become live or die).

5. The "blocks" displayed in the trace are tensors. Different tensors are represented with different colors. Each tensor is alive for certain period of program counter (>=1), so even though there is a gap between two PCs, we use the same color to represent the same tensor. E.g,  in the above graph, the green blocks circled in red are representing one tensor that is alive from step 827 to 833. 

6. When we click a specific tensor, we can see certain attributes associated with that tensor. E.g, if we click one of the green blocks in the circle, we will see the information like below. Where we can see that the tensor name , the starting address (offset), and the tensor size in bytes.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/49965641/97818405-18e00880-1c57-11eb-93cd-2e91d0db1e70.png)


7. For each step, we have a summary tensor which sits at the beginning of the trace, marked with black color. It contains information of about tensors for that time step. E.g, if we click one of the black block, we will get the following information. Where we can see the total number of bytes allocated for that step, the used bytes and the free bytes (fragmentation), and the corresponding performance. 

There is another attribute which is called "bytes for pattern". Since we can customize to plot only a subset of tensors (e.g.,  gradients, or output of certain nodes),  This attribute is to show among all the "alive tensors" of that step, how many bytes are the tensors below to the subgroup that is plotted. Here since we plot all statically planed activations, so the bytes for pattern is equal to total bytes.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/49965641/97818445-5349a580-1c57-11eb-9bf1-d149567cfa38.png)

To customize a session:
1. To record certain tensors of interest. When building the graph, we after creating a nodedef/argdef, we can add the following function:
```
    //Create sessions in the profiler.
    //p_name: session name
    //pid: sessionid
    //map_type: Initalizer, static_activation, dynamic_activation. We have this separtion because they are using different memory offsets.
    //group_name: The group_name that is recorded previously using function "AddRecordingTensorGroup". Used for generating customized sessions for a group of tensors
    //Top_k: The steps with the top-k highest memory consumptions are plot. When top_k == 0, we plot all the steps
    //device_t: The type of the device where the tensors are.
    static void CreateEvents(const std::string& p_name, const size_t pid, const MemoryInfo::MapType& map_type, const std::string& group_name,
                             const size_t top_k, const OrtDevice::DeviceType device_t = OrtDevice::GPU);
```
2.  To record certain tensors of interest. When building the graph, we after creating a nodedef/argdef, we can add the following function:
```
static void AddRecordingTensorGroup(const std::string& group_name, const std::string& tensor_name) 
```
3. To generate the memory trace with name "memory_profile_{local_rank}, for one session run:
``` 
void MemoryInfo::GenerateMemoryProfile() 
```

body:
**Description**: 
The IndexedSubGraph is used to create a Graph instance in the Function body when a Function based node is created for an EP (i.e. not from an ONNX operator with a function based definition). 

After the Node containing the FunctionImpl is created the IndexedSubGraph is invalid, as the nodes it originally referred to have been removed from the main Graph. As such there's no need to store it in the FunctionImpl instance, and nothing actually uses it.

**Motivation and Context**
Remove unused/invalid member.

title: Improve TensorRT engine caching
body:
1. Add engine profile cache
To validate if loaded engine can be used for current inference, engine profile is cached and loaded along with engine. If current input shapes are in the range of the engine profile, the loaded engine can be safely used. Otherwise if input shapes are out of range, profile cache will be updated to cover the new shape and engine will be recreated based on the new profile and also refreshed in the engine cache.
2. Keep one engine and profile cache for each TensorRT subgraph
One engine and one profile will be kept in the cache for each dynamic shape subgraph, but will be updated based on input shapes.
3. Hash graph node size to engine/profile name
4. Use flexbuffers to serialize engine profile
Schema-less flexbuffers are used to serialize the engine profile due to the fact that profile data is small and simple.
5. Assign max shape to optimal profile to improve engine performance
Perf loss is observed in some models if opt profile is set to minimal shape range
6. Enable TensorRT basic tests and add unit test for engine caching
TensorRT basic tests were disabled due to shared library changes. Now it's added back.
